<span id="v.iv.vi.x-p40"></span> [1 Cor. xv.
49](../../../bib/kjv/co1015.htm#049.md)<span id="v.iv.vi.x-p40.1"></span>.
T. argues from the reading <span class="Greek"><span
id="v.iv.vi.x-p40.2"></span>φορέσωμεν</span> (instead of <span
class="Greek"><span id="v.iv.vi.x-p40.3"></span>φορέσομεν</span>), which
indeed was read by many of the fathers, and (what is still more
important) is found in the *Codex Sinaiticus*. We add the critical note
of Dean Alford on this reading: “ACDFKL rel latt copt goth, Theodotus,
Basil, Cæsarius, Cyril, Macarius, Methodius (who prefixes <span
class="Greek"><span id="v.iv.vi.x-p40.4"></span>ἕνα</span>), Chrysostom,
Epiphanius, Ps. Athanasius, Damascene, Irenæus (int), Tertullian,
Cyprian, Hilary, Jerome.”  Alford retains the usual <span
class="Greek"><span id="v.iv.vi.x-p40.5"></span>φορέσομεν</span>, on the
strength chiefly of the *Codex Vaticanus*.

